  "local_port": 44920,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "05 Tacoma 4 cylinder has slight vibration while stopped at a light, why?",
  "response": "A slight vibration in a 2005 Toyota Tacoma with a 4-cylinder engine while stopped at a light can be caused by several factors. Here are some common reasons:\n\n1. **Idle Air Control Valve (IACV) Issues**: The IACV regulates the engine's idle speed. If it\u2019s dirty or malfunctioning, it can cause irregular idle or vibrations.\n\n2. **Engine Mounts**: Worn or damaged engine mounts can allow more engine vibration to transfer to the vehicle\u2019s frame, especially at idle.\n\n3. **Spark Plugs or Ignition System**: Worn spark plugs, faulty ignition coils, or a weak ignition system can cause misfires or rough idle, leading to vibrations.\n\n4. **Fuel System Problems**: Clogged fuel injectors, a dirty fuel filter, or a weak fuel pump can result in uneven fuel delivery, causing the engine to idle roughly.\n\n5. **Vacuum Leaks**: Unmetered air entering the engine through a vacuum leak can disrupt the air-fuel mixture, leading to a rough idle and vibrations.\n\n6. **Dirty Throttle Body**: A buildup of carbon deposits in the throttle body can restrict airflow and cause irregular idle.\n\n7. **Transmission Issues**: If the torque converter is not disengaging properly when the vehicle is stopped, it can cause vibrations.\n\n8. **Excessive Engine Load**: Accessories like the air conditioning compressor or alternator can put extra load on the engine at idle, causing slight vibrations.\n\n9. **Low Engine Oil or Poor Oil Quality**: Insufficient or degraded engine oil can increase engine friction and cause vibrations.\n\n10. **Carbon Buildup**: Carbon deposits on the intake valves or combustion chambers can disrupt engine efficiency and cause rough idle.\n\n### Steps to Diagnose and Resolve:\n- **Scan for Codes**: Use an OBD-II scanner to check for any stored trouble codes that might point to a specific issue.\n- **Inspect Engine Mounts**: Check for cracks or separation in the engine mounts.\n- **Clean Throttle Body and IACV**: Remove and clean the throttle body and idle air control valve.\n- **Check Spark Plugs and Ignition System**: Inspect spark plugs, wires, and ignition coils for wear or damage.\n- **Look for Vacuum Leaks**: Inspect vacuum hoses and connections for cracks or leaks.\n- **Change Engine Oil**: Ensure the engine oil is at the proper level and in good condition.\n\nIf the issue persists after basic troubleshooting, it may require professional diagnosis and repair.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
